Section 3.8.1: all exercises

# 1. What is the problem with this plot? How could you improve it?
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point()

There’s lot of overlap of the dots. Setting some jitter can fix that.

mpg_gg <- ggplot(mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy))
mpg_gg +
  geom_jitter()

  1. What parameters to geom_jitter() control the amount of jittering?
?geom_jitter

width and height

  1. Compare and contrast geom_jitter() with geom_count().
mpg_gg +
  geom_jitter()

mpg_gg +
  geom_count()

geom_jitter adds jitter to overlapping points where as geom_count makes the overlapping points look bigger on the plot

  1. What’s the default position adjustment for geom_boxplot()? Create a visualisation of the mpg dataset that demonstrates it.
?geom_boxplot
# Boxplots are automatically dodged when any aesthetic is a factor
# p + geom_boxplot(aes(colour = drv))

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_boxplot(position = "dodge") +
  coord_flip()

Default postion adjustment is dodge

Section 3.9.1: #2 and #4 only

  1. What does labs() do? Read the documentation.
?labs
# example(labs)

It lets you add title, subtitle, caption, tag, label to the graphs

  1. What does the plot below tell you about the relationship between city and highway mpg? Why is coord_fixed() important? What does geom_abline() do?
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline() +
  coord_fixed()

The plot shows that the highway mileage is better than the city mileage– meaning, better fuel efficiency on highways that in the cities.

  1. Why is NA ^ 0 not missing? Why is NA | TRUE not missing? Why is FALSE & NA not missing? Can you figure out the general rule? (NA * 0 is a tricky counterexample!)

Anything power 0 is 1, so, NA ^ 0 always evaluates to 1 NA | TRUE always evaluates to TRUE because at least one of the operator is TRUE FALSE & NA always evaluates to FALSE because at least one of the operator is FALSE

  1. What does the one_of() function do? Why might it be helpful in conjunction with this vector?
vars <- c("year", "month", "day", "dep_delay", "arr_delay")
select(flights, one_of(vars))
## # A tibble: 336,776 x 5

It’s making select pick the rows that are in the vector vars
